{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489550","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489550"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:20:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:20:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"689"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/689"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.06,0.04,0.16,0.52]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"689"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114698"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/689"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"689"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96701"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"121"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2115"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12348"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12349"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48079"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114698","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114698"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man has a computed tomography (CT) scan of his abdomen and pelvis performed as part of the investigation of an episode of acute abdominal pain which is eventually diagnosed as gallstone-related pancreatitis. His pancreatitis resolves with supportive care and a laparoscopic cholecystectomy is planned as an elective procedure. However, the CT shows a 2.2 cm enhancing lesion in the lower pole of the left kidney and the possible diagnosis of a renal cell carcinoma is raised. His medical history includes a myocardial infarct six months ago with insertion of a coronary stent. His medications include ticagrelor and aspirin.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management of this patient\u0027s renal mass?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fine needle aspiration cytology (FNA)","Left radical nephrectomy","Stereotactic ablative radiotherapy (SABR)","Left partial nephrectomy","Surveillance"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is an example of a common clinical problem known as the small renal mass (SRM). Given the increased utilisation of cross-sectional imaging of the abdomen for many indications there are increasing numbers of small renal lesions being identified which may or may not represent a clinically significant malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERenal cell carcinoma (RCC) is suggested on CT imaging by the presence of a solid enhancing (\u0026gt;20 Hounsfield units difference between contrast and non-contrast phases) or complex cystic mass arising from the parenchyma of the kidney. The risk of metastatic disease with an RCC \u0026lt;3cm is small and the annual rate of metastasis is 1%. Furthermore, some low-grade malignancies are slow to progress and may stay stable for many years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the first instance \u003Cstrong\u003Esurveillance\u003C/strong\u003E of this mass is completely reasonable. A contrast-enhanced CT scan should be repeated in 6 months time to re-evaluate the lesion and establish a growth rate. Given the patient has recently had a myocardial infarction and is on dual anti-platelet therapy this is even more reason to avoid surgical intervention (such as \u003Cstrong\u003Epartial nephrectomy \u003C/strong\u003Ewhich may or may not be feasible given the location of the mass, or \u003Cstrong\u003Eradical nephrectomy\u003C/strong\u003E) and survey the lesion in the first instance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFNA\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically performed for renal lesions if the imaging findings are highly suggestive of malignancy. If biopsy was to be indicated (which would also require cessation of anti-platelet medications) then a core biopsy would be performed, not FNA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESABR\u003C/strong\u003E is typically reserved for patients who are too co-morbid to consider surgical intervention and have renal malignancy that requires treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Small renal cell carcinomas in older patients can be managed with active surveillance."],"references":["Mir MC, Capitanio U, Bertolo R, Ouzaid I, Salagierski M, Kriegmair M, et al. Role of Active Surveillance for Localized Small Renal Masses. Eur. Uro Oncol. 2018;1:177-87. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31102618/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96701"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"689"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96701","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96701"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-18T20:57:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-18T20:58:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"689"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114698"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"